{"file_path": "compromise-ica-terms.md", "new_string": "**Economic quantification.** Mandatory assumption would require the 2L group to take on up to **$125 million** of open-ended contingent funding obligations — an obligation the 2L group's fund vehicle is structurally prohibited from assuming. Making assumption optional removes this deal-breaker while preserving the 1L Agent's ability to have the Revolver assumed (and Meridian's committed liquidity preserved) where the purchaser is able and willing to do so. Where the purchaser does not assume, the unfunded commitments terminate on consummation of the purchase, and the First Lien Agent agrees to use commercially reasonable efforts to facilitate replacement revolving commitments — protecting Meridian's ongoing liquidity access without forcing the 2L group to violate its fund constraints.

The 1L Agent's position letter argues that mandatory assumption is necessary to prevent a "bifurcation of the First Lien syndicate" into purchasing 2L holders of funded debt and remaining Revolver lenders holding unfunded commitments, which the 1L contends would create intractable conflicts regarding voting rights, collateral allocation, and enforcement decisions, and would deprive Meridian of assured access to the full $125 million Revolver. The compromise addresses this concern directly: where the purchaser does not elect to assume, the unfunded Revolver commitments terminate cleanly on consummation of the purchase (rather than remaining outstanding and held by a fragmented group), and the First Lien Agent covenants to use commercially reasonable efforts to facilitate replacement revolving commitments — so there is no lingering bifurcated syndicate and Meridian's path to replacement liquidity is preserved. Where the purchaser does elect to assume, the 1L Agent's preferred outcome is achieved in full. The compromise thus eliminates the structural bifurcation risk the 1L identifies while accommodating the 2L's fund-vehicle constraint, which the 2L Agent has traced to Ridgeline's Amended and Restated Agreement of Limited Partnership, dated as of March 1, 2021 (the "Limited Partnership Agreement"), and which restricts the fund's ability to enter into open-ended commitment obligations requiring future capital calls on an uncertain and potentially accelerated schedule.

**Economic impracticability at full draw (2L Agent's concern).** The 2L Agent's position letter argues that a par-only purchase price renders the purchase right "economically impracticable" at full draw, because the 2L would have to deploy approximately $484.3 million (funded par at the non-default rate, 90-day accrual) to acquire senior obligations, bringing the 2L's total capital at risk to approximately $634.3 million (its existing $150 million plus the purchase price) — a figure approaching the appraised TEV of $640 million and exceeding any realistic distressed TEV. The compromise materially mitigates this concern relative to the 1L Agent's opening position: by adopting the non-default rate (saving ~$2.375 million on a 90-day accrual versus the default rate) and by making revolver assumption optional (removing the $125 million contingent obligation the 1L Agent would have mandated), the compromise reduces the funded capital the 2L must deploy and eliminates the open-ended contingent exposure, keeping the purchase right within the range of economic rationality for the 2L in the distressed scenarios in which it would be exercised. The 2L Agent's counsel has confirmed that par for funded debt "may be acceptable" precisely when paired with these accommodations, which the compromise provides.", "old_string": "**Economic quantification.** Mandatory assumption would require the 2L group to take on up to **$125 million** of open-ended contingent funding obligations — an obligation the 2L group's fund vehicle is structurally prohibited from assuming. Making assumption optional removes this deal-breaker while preserving the 1L Agent's ability to have the Revolver assumed (and Meridian's committed liquidity preserved) where the purchaser is able and willing to do so. Where the purchaser does not assume, the unfunded commitments terminate on consummation of the purchase, and the First Lien Agent agrees to use commercially reasonable efforts to facilitate replacement revolving commitments — protecting Meridian's ongoing liquidity access without forcing the 2L group to violate its fund constraints."}

